        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-03-17T18:38:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-03-17T18:38:00-05:00" n="234"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d234">
                <head>234. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in the United Arab
                        Republic<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d234fn1">Source: Department of
                        State, Central Files, 786B.5–<gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/3–1759.
                        Confidential. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_BWD1">Brewer</persName> and
                            <persName corresp="#p_KDD1">Kennedy</persName>; cleared with <persName
                            corresp="#p_RWM1">Rountree</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MRD1"
                            >Murphy</persName>, <gloss target="#t_ICA1">ICA</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_E1">E</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_G1">G</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_H1">H</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_WMSC1">W/MSC</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_BNA1">BNA</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>;
                        and approved and signed for <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName> by
                            <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName>. Repeated to Beirut,
                        Baghdad, London, and Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1959-03-17T18:38:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 17, 1959—6:38 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2729. Joint State–<gloss target="#t_ICA1">ICA</gloss> message. In effort maintain
                    momentum in improving US relations with <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>
                    Department has decided it would now be appropriate remove remaining limitations
                    on use of aid funds.<note n="2" xml:id="d234fn2">This decision was approved by
                            <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> in a memorandum, also
                        dated March 17, from <persName corresp="#p_RWM1">Rountree</persName>. (<hi
                            rend="italic">Ibid</hi>.)</note> We accordingly plan inform <gloss
                        target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> that <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss>
                    prepared institute discussions Cairo immediately re agreement on use of Egyptian
                    pounds from <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 sales in 1955–56. Steps to be
                    taken involve negotiation of loan agreement and subsequent mutual agreement re
                    use of funds for economic development in Egyptian Region under Section 104(g) of
                        <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480. Exact amount that would be available
                    is at present uncertain due to shortfall in sales and exchange rate
                    complications but will be somewhat less than $13.6 million.</p>
                <p>Since <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> Ambassador officially requested <gloss
                        target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> release these funds some months ago, <gloss
                        target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> planning, after informing UK, communicate
                    decision to <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> Ambassador here along foregoing
                    lines. We will advise you of date he informed so that you may inform <persName
                        corresp="#p_NM1">Nasser</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KAM1"
                        >Kaissouni</persName> and other <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>
                    officials of US decision and take initiative arrange any working level
                    discussions that may be necessary in Cairo with respect details reactivation
                    this assistance.</p>
                <p>Subject your views, <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> not contemplating any
                    publicity this development.</p>
                <pb facs="0553" n="519" xml:id="pg_519"/>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss> We would also plan include normal provision
                    use local currency for economic development purposes in any new <gloss
                        target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 agreement which may be concluded with <gloss
                        target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>. However, believe it unnecessary inform <gloss
                        target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> this fact except in context new negotiations.
                    End <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>.<note n="3" xml:id="d234fn3">On March
                        23, <persName corresp="#p_HRG1">Hare</persName> was informed that the
                        British concurred. (Telegram 2813 to Cairo; <hi rend="italic">ibid.,</hi>
                            786B.5–<gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/3–2359) On the same day,
                            <persName corresp="#p_RWM1">Rountree</persName> told Ambassador
                            <persName corresp="#p_KM1">Kamel</persName>. (Memorandum of
                        conversation; <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>.)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Herter</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
